observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Inventory Committee to completely conduct a physical count of all properties of the Municipal Government of Donsol (MGD);  

Submit the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) to the Audit Team (AT) on or before January 31 of the ensuing year; 


Reconcile the RPCPPE with the property and accounting records; 

Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;

Consider the hiring or designating personnel who will be responsible for the General Services Office (GSO), hence, the Office may be able to fully function, especially on the maintenance and keeping of complete and updated PPE records and reports;

Require the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) to prepare and maintain computerized records of the PPE Ledger Cards (PPELC), Real Property Ledger Cards and Construction in Progress Ledger Cards;

Provide complete details of the individual PPE accounts including, but not limited to the exact location, hence, to ease the inspection/inventory of the property; 

Request all the necessary documents related to the PPEs/Infrastructure Projects implemented by other government agencies for use and maintenance by the MGD in order to properly recognize the assets in accordance with the provisions of the International Public Sector Accounting Standards;

Require the MAO to prepare the necessary correcting entry to reclassify the properties amounting to ₱249,730.00, with acquisition costs below ₱50,000.00, as Inventories if not yet issued, otherwise as appropriate Expense accounts if already issued;

Require the MAO and the GSO to strengthen controls on handling and recording procedures for PPE accounts by performing periodic reconciliation of records, and ensuring that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted accordingly in the books; and

Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items.

We recommended that the Management:

Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and the Municipal Engineer to plan properly and efficiently all procurement activities pertaining to these developmental PPAs to fast-track the implementation and completion thereof; 

Require the Municipal Development Council and all other implementing offices of the MGD to step up their concerted efforts, ensure optimum utilization of the 20% DF and implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe to achieve the timely delivery of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes; 

Conduct an extensive review of the continuing PPAs to determine whether those projects are still feasibly implementable and reprogram those that are considered non-priority PPAs; and

Refrain from appropriating a minimal amount of budget to specific PPAs hence implementation of the same may be set aside due to prioritization of PPAs with larger budget.

We recommended that the LCE require the:

Municipal Engineer to provide the MA and the Designated Property Officer the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects as basis for recording in their respective subsidiary records and facilitate the preparation of the Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Networks (RPCLRN);

The Inventory Committee to conduct yearly the required physical inventory of local roads owned by the MGD, prepare and submit the RPCLRN to the AT within the prescribed deadline;

Property Custodian to maintain Local Road Inventory and updated Road Map and keep complete LRN Property Cards (LRNPC) for all roads and its components using the prescribed format illustrated in the Circular;

MA to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same with the LRNPCs and the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year to ensure proper recording and control of the assets; 

MA to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the MGD in the Notes to the FS; and 

MA to re-compute the accumulated depreciation and depreciation expense and thereafter prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the year-end balances of the Public Infrastructure – Road Networks and Government Equity accounts.

We recommended that Management require the:

Inventory Committee to willfully conduct the required physical count of all inventory items, prepare the corresponding RPCI and submit the same to the AT within the prescribed period; 

MT or the acting Storekeeper, in his behalf, and the MA to prepare and maintain the Stock Cards and the Subsidiary Ledger Cards, respectively, and to conduct periodic reconciliation of the Inventory records in accordance with the existing rules and regulations.

Nevertheless, we recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the Municipal Accountant (MA) to provide a schedule for the cash deficiency noted in the TF;
Continue to exercise diligence, prudence and proper control in the disposition of the MGD’s funds while limiting expenditures within the total income realized and collected during the year to avoid cash deficiency;
Invest the idle cash in major infrastructure projects or other PPAs that can help improve the livelihood and general welfare of the MGD’s constituents. However, relative to the audit observation on the discrepancy of cash balances between the records of the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) and the Municipal Treasury Office (MTO), the said Offices shall reconcile first their records to arrive at the correct amount of cash savings that will be available for appropriation; and
Require the finance committee to prepare a Cash Analysis monthly/quarterly and submit the same to the LCE for reference in decision-making purposes.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
The Inventory Committee to completely conduct a physical count of all properties of the MGD;
Submit the corresponding RPCPPE to the AT on or before January 31 of the ensuing year;
Reconcile the RPCPPE with the property and accounting records;
Reconcile the PPELC and the amount presented in the FS;
Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;
The LCE should consider hiring or designating personnel who will be responsible for the GSO. Hence, the Office may be able to fully function, especially in the maintenance and keeping of complete and updated PPE records and reports;
Require the MAO to prepare and maintain an updated computerized records of the PPELCs and RPLC;
Provide complete details of the individual PPE accounts, including but not limited to the exact location hence to ease the inspection/inventory of the property; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items.

We recommended and Management agreed that the:
Property Office maintains the SPC, RegSPI and other records and reports as required in the COA Circular 2022-004;
MAO prepares and maintains the SPLC;
IC conducts the annual physical inventory of semi-expendable properties and prepare and submit the RPCSP; and
Management shall issue an updated policy/memorandum determining/providing the estimated useful life of the MGD’s semi-expendable properties, as necessary.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
The BAC, the Secretariat, and the TWG strictly abide by the standards set forth by RA No. 9184, its Revised IRR and other relevant laws on government procurement;
All concerned officials/employees exercise due diligence in the performance of their duties to ensure that all requirements of the procurement law are faithfully adhered to;
The MA shall observe the requirements of COA Circular No. 2012-001 at all times in processing transactions; and
Ensure that the approved CSHP is submitted before the execution of the contract following the provision of RA No. 9184;

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Instruct the BAC and the Municipal Engineer (ME) to plan properly and efficiently all procurement activities pertaining to these developmental PPAs to fast-track the implementation and completion thereof;
Require the Municipal Development Council and all other implementing offices of the MGD to step up their concerted efforts, ensure optimum utilization of the 20% DF and implement the PPAs within the targeted timeframe to achieve the timely delivery of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes;
Conduct an extensive review of the continuing PPAs to determine whether those projects are still feasibly implementable and reprogram those that are considered non-priority PPAs;
Refrain from appropriating a minimal amount of budget to specific PPAs; hence, implementation of the same may be set aside due to prioritization of PPAs with larger budgets;
Consolidate the implementation of similar PPAs with minimal budgets into a clustered project that can be implemented as one consolidated PPA; and
Open a separate bank account for the 20 DF henceforth to ease the monitoring of transactions pertaining to the said fund.
We also recommended and Management agreed that each department responsible for the maintenance of records and reports pertaining to the 20% DF conduct reconciliations to avoid undermining the credibility of the reported data.

We recommended and Management agreed that the LCE requires the HRMU to:
Establish a formalized process and timeline for the renewal of JO contracts to ensure timely and consistent engagement of personnel.  This should include the development of written procedures for evaluating the performance of JO personnel, along with proper documentation of the evaluation results.  These records should serve as the basis for contract renewal decisions and support greater transparency, accountability, and merit-based reappointments.;
Ensure coordination between Human Resources and requesting units for the timely initiation of renewal documentation.;
Limit the hiring/deployment of JO personnel to those offices that are extremely in need of their services;
Incorporate in the JO contract the number of man-hours, quantity and duration of the work to be performed by the JO personnel and require them to submit quantified accomplishment reports and signed copies of contracts to support payment of wages.

We reiterated our prior years’ recommendation that Management:

Continue to issue demand letters compelling the AOs or employees to settle immediately in full their outstanding CAs, either by liquidation, by payment/refund or through salary deductions;


Obtain the necessary documents to support the request for write-off of the outstanding CAs of the deceased AO and submit the same to the AT in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular 20-005 as amended by COA Circular No. 2023-008; 

Ensure that all CA are liquidated at year-end in compliance with COA Circular No. 97-002 (d); and

Comply strictly with the requirements of Section 89 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 97-002 and all related rules and regulations pertaining to granting and liquidation of CAs.

We recommended that the LCE direct:

The MDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMF Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP in accordance with the format provided in COA Circular No. 2012-002 and with a complete list of targeted PPAs to be funded by the LDRRMF current appropriations and updated unexpended prior year fund balances;

The MDRRMO to submit the LDRRMFIP to COA and the concerned departments of the LGU; 

The MA to prepare and submit the revised Notes to FS for LDRRMF to the AT;

The MDRRMO, MA and MBO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their records to ensure the correctness of the reported amounts for the appropriation and utilization of the LDRRMF; 

The MA and the MT to perform appropriate actions to revert the unexpended balance of the Special Trust Fund for CY 2018 to the GF; and

The MA and MT to determine the composition of the additional cash available in the bank accounts for LDRRM for the proper appropriation and subsequent utilization thereof.

We recommended that Management:

Provide appropriation for the insurance of the selected insurable properties;

Submit the consolidated Property Insurance Form (PIF) starting CY 2025 to the Supervising Auditor/AT Leader and the General Insurance Fund (GIF), GSIS not later than April 30 of each year in accordance with COA Circular 2018-002;

Fill out completely the PIF, data such as property number, market/appraised value/insurable interest, date of appraisal and remarks or other important information related to individual assets shall be provided;

Ensure that insurable properties are properly covered with insurance with the GIF of the GSIS to compensate any risk associated with the MGD properties/assets; and

Submit a copy of insurance policies to the AT for verification/audit.

We commended Management for being duly recognized as a passer of the Seal of Good Local Governance under the category of Environmental Management for CY 2023 and the support to NGO that resulted in the grand prize (1st place) for national level of Women in Action for Environment Award – Outstanding Women Organization Partners for Environment.  

We likewise recommended that the Management:

Expedite implementation of the project for the creation of functional Material Recovery Facility (MRF)/Residual Containment Area, hence, to maximize the use of machinery and equipment for the processing of solid wastes;

Continue and enhance the PPAs that address issues related to SWM and environmental protection;

Continue the support to various organizations related to SWM and environmental programs;

Instruct the Environment Management Unit to continue the efforts in requiring the barangays for the utilization and full functionality of the barangay MRFs and encourage the barangay to activate the Barangay Solid Waste Management Committee; and

Continue the conduct of Information Education Campaign and orientation relative to the SWM and environmental protection, especially on the proper segregation of wastes including the imposition of fines and penalties thereon.

We recommended that Management:

Prepare the APP based on the prescribed format as provided by the Government Procurement Policy Board; 

Ensure that all Project Prcurement Management Plan (PPMPs) are properly consolidated and procurements are entirely incorporated to reflect transparency of procurement activities within the Municipality;

Advise the Local Finance Committee, Municipal Development Council and other concerned departments to plan meticulously the PPAs to be funded, hence, avoid appropriating small amounts of fund to PPAs that may not be implemented during the budget year;

Remind the BAC to adopt competitive bidding as a default mode of procurement in accordance with Section 10 of RA No. 9184, except as provided for in Article XVI of this Act.  Henceforth, the BAC and other concerned officials and employees to carefully propose the mode of procurement in the APP that may be adopted during the implementation of the targeted PPAs;

Ensure to invite the observers in all stages of the procurement process;

Instruct the BAC to print and ensure that the ITB attached to the claim/disbursement voucher is in “active” status;

Post the Notice of Award (NOA), approved contracts and Notice to Proceed (NTP) in the Philippine Government Electronic Procurement System (PhilGEPS), in the agency website and in conspicuous places in accordance with the provisions of the RIRR of RA No. 9184;

Provide written explanation or justification for resorting to piecemeal procurement for the construction materials of infrastructure projects;

Require the contractor/supplier to post performance security before the perfection of the contract;

Ensure that the approved Construction and Safety Health Program (CSHP) is submitted before the execution of the contract following the provision of RA No. 9184; 

Instruct the concerned official to prepare and attach as part of the SDs the detailed engineering certification at all times for the procurement of infrastructure projects; and 

Ensure that the BAC, its Secretariat and Technical Working Group members, including other relevant procurement personnel, are directed to attend procurement training or other related capacity development programs.

We recommended that the LCE require the members of the BAC and the LSB to:

Provide an explanation or justification for resorting to piecemeal procurement and reimbursements for the procurement of the above-mentioned goods charged to SEF;

Consolidate the PPMPs of the different districts/schools into one APP;

Avoid procuring similar goods from the same supplier in several transactions through piecemeal procurement; and

Use public bidding as the primary mode of procurement, except as provided for in Article XVI of the RIRR of RA No. 9184.

We recommended that Management require: 

The BAC to review the Purchase Requests and Request for Quotations for completeness of vital information; 

The Procurement Unit to submit the Purchase Orders and its SDs within five days from the perfection of the contract to the AT;  

The concerned personnel in charge of inspecting and accepting deliveries of procured items to fill-out completely the Acceptance and Inspection Reports and notify the AT of the date and time of scheduled deliveries within 24 hours from acceptance thereof.  Henceforth, liquidated damages for late/delayed deliveries of purchased supplies/goods may be deducted; and 

Include the brand names, together with the specifications of the items quoted by the supplier in response to the advertised relevant characteristics and/or performance requirements of the items needed by the agency in the POs to serve as reference during deliveries, inspection and acceptance by Management.

We recommended that the LCE require:

All requesting units to accomplish properly the POs and submit the same within five days from the perfection of the contract to the AT.  Henceforth, payment for late/delayed deliveries of purchased supplies/goods be deducted of liquidated damages equivalent to one-tenth (1/10) of one percent for every day of delay;

The concerned personnel in charge with inspecting and accepting deliveries of procured items to fill-out completely the IAR and notify the AT of the date and time of scheduled deliveries within 24 hours from acceptance hereof; and

We recommended that the LCE require the:
Municipal Engineer to provide the MA and the Designated Property Officer the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects as basis for recording in their respective subsidiary records and facilitate the preparation of the RPCLRN;
The Inventory Committee to conduct yearly the required physical inventory of local roads owned by the MGD, prepare and submit the RPCLRN to the AT within the prescribed deadline;
Property Custodian to maintain Local Road Inventory and updated Road Map and keep complete LRNPCs for all roads and its components using the prescribed format illustrated in the Circular;
MA to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same with the LRNPCs and the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year to ensure proper recording and control of the assets;
MA to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the MGD in the Notes to the FS; and
MA to re-compute the accumulated depreciation and depreciation expense and thereafter prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the year-end balances of the Public Infrastructure – Road Networks and Government Equity accounts.

We recommended that the LCE require the:
Municipal Human Resource Management Office (MHRMO) to submit a copy of the Minutes of Meeting directing the Department Heads to do the scheduling of employees who reported for duty during the pandemic;
Department Heads to submit the schedule of employees required to work during the pandemic stating the dates and purpose of work as directed by the LCE;
Municipal Health Officer to submit the schedule of PHWs required to work during the pandemic as directed by the LCE;
Chief of Offices concerned to submit the authority of personnel in the payrolls to physically report for work in their assigned hospital/health facility, offices or work stations, the prescribed official working hours and dates attended during ECQ;
The personnel listed in the payroll who received AHDP and SRA to submit duly signed and approved DTRs as basis for their actual presence as required by the head or chief of offices; and
MA to closely verify the correctness of the payrolls, disbursements or liquidation reports to ensure validity of transactions.

We recommended that the LCE require the MA to identify the status and establish the correct balance of the Due to NGAs account for each SA and thereafter:
return/refund to the concerned SA the unutilized balance of the fund transfer wherein the agreement requires the return thereof;
revert to the Government Equity the balances of the fund transfers in nature of financial assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual budgeting, accounting and auditing laws, rules and regulations;
retain special purpose funds; or
clean the books of accounts in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 in order to present fairly the Liability account in the FS.

We recommended that LCE require the MA to:
Reconcile the Due to LGUs – PGS account balance with the  corresponding balance per PGS books.  Thereafter, remit immediately the reconciled balance to the PGS.  On the other hand, close the Due to LGUs – CGS to Government Equity account;
Trace the sources and/or purposes of those balances that need further validation for proper recording and presentation in the FS, particularly those SAs not considered as LGUs.  If validity of claimants could not be established, return/remit to the Bureau of Treasury the balances with sufficient money back-up.
Revert to the Government Equity the balances of the fund transfers/collections in nature of assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual budgeting, accounting and auditing laws, rules and regulations;
Initiate immediate utilization of the balances of special purpose funds for the benefit of targeted stakeholders; and
Turn-over/Transfer to the SK the unexpended/excess funds attributable to the SK.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management instruct the GFPS to:
Ensure proper monitoring of planned GAD PAPs and the full implementation and utilization of GPB;
Continue completing, updating and maintaining the GAD database of information necessary for proper gender-responsive planning, programming, policy formation and in addressing priority gender issues;
Identify GAD activities in regular programs with attributed GPB using the HGDG; and
Support the GAR with the required reports/documents and furnish the same to the AT to facilitate audit of GAD.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

Create an Inventory Committee, preferably composed of the Planning and Development Office, Engineering Office, Treasurer’s Office, General Services Office, Accountant’s Office and Assessor Office to conduct an inspection and inventory of all road networks.

The created inventory committee shall conduct a physical count/inventory of all the Municipal roads and reconcile it with the Municipal Road Map and determine the existence and condition of the road components of each road for proper measurement and valuation using the prescribed forms such as: i) Local Road and Bridge Inventory and Condition Survey; ii) Report of Local Road Network; and iii) Report on the Physical Count of Local Road Network;

Direct the MAO to exert best effort to gather all details and information needed to determine the cost of the road lot, road components and its depreciable life of each road network and reconcile it with the recorded cost in the RPI and existing ledgers.

Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the recognition of Public Infrastructure – Roads, Highways and Bridges in the GL as of December 31, 2020 after ensuring that the accounting and reporting procedures laid down under COA Circular No. 2015-008 were fully complied by the concerned offices.  Also, the same procedures shall be undertaken for other public infrastructures accounts;

Direct the MAO and the General Services Office to strictly prepare and maintain all the prescribed reports under COA Circular No. 2015-008;

Direct the Planning and Development Office to maintain the information on the local road network of the Municipality, particularly, the plans and programs of the construction, repair and maintenance of local roads and the depreciable life of the road networks in coordination with the Engineering Office;

Direct the Engineering Office to enhance the existing Local Road Network map aligned to the requirement of a road map described under the Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG) Memorandum Circular No. 2017-159 and Local Roads Assets Management Manual for LGUs.

As the office that undertakes the construction and repair of the local roads, documents relative thereto shall be maintained so that the necessary and detailed information of a certain road project, such as complete description of the road and the cost segregation of the road components are available anytime when needed by the accounting and general services office and other stakeholders; and

Direct the Assessor’s Office to prepare and maintain the tax maps, which are used as basis for identifying the ownership of all the road lots in the city road network and also assists in determining the cost of the road lots with no available costs.

We recommended that Management instruct the GFPS to:

Continue the completion, updating and maintaining the GAD Database timely information necessary for proper gender-responsive planning, programming, policy formation and in addressing priority gender issues;

Identify GAD activities through the use of HGDG; update regularly the GAD Plan and identified projects to address the GAD issues and concerns in the Municipality;

Support the GAD AR with the required reports/documents and furnish the same to the Audit Team to facilitate audit of GAD fund utilization; and

Ensure proper monitoring of planned GAD PAPs and the full implementation of GPB.

We also recommended that the LCE issue an Executive Order or Administrative Order creating a GAD M&E Team as required under Section 5.1 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 in order to provide Management with the necessary data and information essential for policy making.

