We recommended that Management instruct:

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to regularly reconcile their respective books/records so that errors and deficiencies are immediately detected and corrected;

The Municipal Accountant to closely supervise the preparation and submission of BRS ensuring that the outputs of the personnel assigned are thoroughly reviewed, and to immediately submit to the Audit Team the complete set of BRS for the accounts under SEF and TF; 


The Municipal Accountant to expedite the verification of reconciling items under the General Fund and effect the necessary adjusting entries; and 


The concerned offices to henceforth comply with the requirements of Section 74 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 96-011 and Section 181 of the GAAM to produce an accurate and more reliable report on the cash accounts of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management:

Compel the concerned Accountable Officers (AOs) to immediately settle in full or refund their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions. Require the AOs to provide a definite period to which deductions shall be made to fully pay their dues, the period which must not exceed one year;

Issue demand letters to and negotiate with the remaining AOs who did not conform with the staggered salary deductions scheme on their preferred manner of payment without setting aside the requirements of pertinent law, rules and regulations;

Implement immediately the directives of COA Circular No. 2012-004 against AOs with outstanding cash advances and seriously consider the necessary sanctions on the failure to liquidate; and

Devise other effective methods to increase the liquidation/payment rate and zero out outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that Management:

Require the business proof of income in the renewal of business permit for the review of the gross receipts/sales declared in the application form that shall be retained by the MTO in the taxpayer’s permanent file for current and future reference;

Include the presumptive income levels to be used in the PILAA in the revision of the Municipal Local Revenue Code;

Review and ensure that all application forms are properly filled out; and

Include the statement required in Section 6.1.1, illustrated in Annex 1 of Department of the Interior and Local Government (DILG)- Department of Trade and Industry (DTI)- Department of Information and Communications (DICT) Joint Memorandum Circular (JMC) No. 01, s. 2016 in the business permit application form.

We recommended that:

the Management establish and maintain a GAD database containing sex-disaggregated data and gender statistics, in compliance with the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;

the Local Chief Executive designate the GAD Focal Point System (GFPS)- Technical Working Group (TWG) Chair and properly identify its members duly endorsed by their supervisors who will catalyze, coordinate, provide direction and monitor the programs and projects on gender and development concerns within the agency and its constituents;

the Local Chief Executive issue an Executive Order or Administrative Order creating a GAD M&E Team as required under Section 5.1 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 in order to provide Management with the much-needed data and information essential for policy making;

the Local Chief Executive direct the GFPS to administer the HGDG tests in order to aid them in the attribution of budgets to the GAD budget and in the determination of PPAs that specifically address the gender gaps/issues and concerns and work towards the attainment of their targeted outputs;

the Management strictly comply with the mechanisms and processes required under PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 for proper identification of existing gender issues to ensure that the approved PPAs to be incorporated in the GPB are gender responsive, doable and realistic; and

the Management direct the GFPS ExeCom to ensure proper monitoring of planned PPAs and the full implementation of GAD Plan and Budget GPB).

Considering the increasing number of unimplemented projects from the 20 per cent DF, we recommended the following:

Collective efforts are enjoined to study the status of all PPAs that need to be implemented so that best strategies may be determined, setbacks are avoided and implementation could run smoothly and expeditiously;

Planning be done meticulously so that priority and more feasible PPAs are identified, budgets are sufficiently appropriated, realignments are avoided, and the period of implementation is realistic;

Revert to the General Fund for reappropriation all excess balances of projects already implemented; and

Exert vigorous efforts in the implementation of all unimplemented PPAs and ensure that at the end of the succeeding year, unimplemented projects are diminished, if not all finished.

We recommended that Management instruct:
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to regularly reconcile their respective books/records so that errors and deficiencies are immediately detected and corrected;
The Municipal Accountant to closely supervise the preparation and submission of BRS ensuring that the outputs of the personnel assigned are thoroughly reviewed, and to immediately submit to the Audit Team the complete set of BRS for the accounts under SEF and TF;
The Municipal Accountant to expedite the verification of reconciling items under the GF and effect the necessary adjusting entries; and
The concerned offices to henceforth comply with the requirements of Section 74 of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 96-011 and Section 181 of the GAAM, Volume I to produce an accurate and more reliable report on the cash accounts of the Municipality.

