To address these deficiencies, we recommended that Management:

Compel the erring Accountable Officers (AOs) to immediately settle in full their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions;

Require the AOs to provide a definite period to which deductions shall be made against their salaries to fully pay their dues, the period of which must not exceed one year;

Demand for the immediate return/refund of cash advances for trainings/seminars which were deferred, cancelled or not attended;

Require the SDO of PNP – Donsol to submit to the Accounting Office and Audit Team the transmittal letters stamped received by COA-Intelligence and Confidential Fund Audit Unit (ICFAU) to prove that the liquidation documents of cash advances for intelligence fund have been forwarded to and received by the same; and

Ensure full compliance with the requirements of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and the related rules and regulations pertaining to cash advances.

We recommended that Management strictly adhere to Sections 22 and 23 of the amendment to Rule XVI of the Omnibus Rules Implementing Book V of EO No. 292 per MC No. 41, s. 1998 on the guidelines on Monetization of Leave Credits.

We also recommended that the HRMO:

Exercise prudence in recommending approval for the grant of leave monetization;

Ensure that officials and employees availing for monetization of vacation leave credits has accumulated no less than 15 days, in which case he can monetize no more than ten days and that five days of VL credits will remain after monetization which shall be availed only once a year;

Avoid approving monetization of more than 30 days leave credits;

Strictly follow the conditions prescribed in Section 23 of the Omnibus Rules on Leave in case officials and employees chose to avail the special monetization; and

Stop allowing the practice of monetizing sick leave or combination of vacation and sick leave credit balances.

Further, we recommended that the Municipal Accountant check the validity and completeness of the supporting documents before processing any payments for leave monetization.

We recommended that Management:

Require the newly appointed LDRRM Officer to religiously comply with the requirements of COA Circular 2012-002 on the preparation and submission of the annual LDRRMF Investment Plan;

Require the Municipal DRRM Office to prepare the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to be certified correct by the Municipal Accountant and submit the same immediately through the LDRRM Council and Local Development Council to the concerned offices on the required dates, pursuant to Section 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002;

Fully utilize the allocated 70 per cent Mitigation Fund of the LDRRMF through aggressive implementation of its targeted PPAs towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;

Make available for use the unexpended DRRMF and direct the LDRRM Council to appropriate the amount for disaster preparedness as provided in the LDRRMF Investment Plan to enhance Management‘s capability for prompt provision of more facilities for disaster preparedness.  Moreover, any unutilized amount after five years must be reverted back to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund and shall be made available for social services after subsequent enactment of the Sangguniang Bayan; and

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to ensure that all charges in the LDRRMF are related to the four thematic areas of disaster risk reduction management as prescribed in Nataional DRRM Council, DBM and DILG JMC No. 2013-01.

We recommended that:

the Management establish and maintain a GAD database containing sex-disaggregated data and gender statistics, in compliance with the PCW, DILG, DBM and NEDA JMC No. 2013-01;

the Local Chief Executive designate the GFPS-TWG Chair and properly identify its members duly endorsed by their supervisors who will catalyze, coordinate, provide direction and monitor the programs and projects on gender and development concerns within the agency and its constituents;

the Local Chief Executive issue an Executive Order or Administrative Order creating a GAD M&E Team as required under Section 5.1 of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 in order to provide Management with the much-needed data and information essential for policy making;

the Local Chief Executive send member/s of the GFPS to trainings on how to use monitoring tools such as HGDG and PIMME;

the Local Chief Executive direct the GFPS to administer the HGDG tests in order to aid them in the attribution of budgets to the GAD budget and in the determination of PPAs that specifically address the gender gaps/issues and concerns and work towards the attainment of their targeted outputs;

the Management strictly comply with the mechanisms and processes required under PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01 as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 for proper identification of existing gender issues to ensure that the approved PPAs to be incorporated in the GPB are gender responsive, doable and realistic; and

the Management direct the GFPS ExeCom to ensure proper monitoring of planned PPAs and the full implementation of GAD Plan and Budget.

